00:37:08.570 --> 00:37:10.100
And I'm confused by that.

00:37:10.100 --> 00:37:16.730
Isn't the fact that you
have such a large sample

00:37:16.730 --> 00:37:20.690
and that they span so
much distance and time

00:37:20.690 --> 00:37:24.890
that statistically you
could get a signal--

00:37:24.890 --> 00:37:29.780
you have a whole range of worlds
from which that could emerge,

00:37:29.780 --> 00:37:33.920
even if they've had a
very short lifespan.

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:39.290
- Well, if they had a short
lifespan, we would have to be--

00:37:39.290 --> 00:37:42.630
let's make it ridiculous.

00:37:42.630 --> 00:37:46.700
Let's say that somehow
the technology arose,

00:37:46.700 --> 00:37:50.840
and 10 years later, it did
itself in, it blew itself up,

00:37:50.840 --> 00:37:52.850
destroyed its world, whatever.

00:37:52.850 --> 00:37:56.450
We would have to
choose and be very

00:37:56.450 --> 00:38:01.610
lucky to be looking at
that particular world

00:38:01.610 --> 00:38:03.260
during those 10 years.

00:38:03.260 --> 00:38:05.574
- So just the fact
that we're looking

00:38:05.574 --> 00:38:07.230
at a very small sample--

00:38:07.230 --> 00:38:09.080
- No, we're going to
look at a large sample,

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:11.750
but the fact that you
would have to hit them

00:38:11.750 --> 00:38:17.120
in just the right 10
years, it makes it much--

00:38:17.120 --> 00:38:20.150
statistically, what
you're going to detect

00:38:20.150 --> 00:38:22.051
is the long-lived civilizations.

00:38:27.210 --> 00:38:27.710
- Hi.

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:28.680
My name's Siobhan.

00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:31.340
