00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:28.760
- Hmm?

00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:30.260
- Blink once for yes.

00:40:30.260 --> 00:40:31.675
- Yeah, right.

00:40:31.675 --> 00:40:32.175
Exactly.

00:40:32.175 --> 00:40:32.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:32.850 --> 00:40:33.720
It's not quite that.

00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:34.650
But there is a--

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:36.300
we do have a false
faith that when

00:40:36.300 --> 00:40:40.770
we observe that,
yes, we don't expect

00:40:40.770 --> 00:40:42.750
that that will be an issue.

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:47.120
Certainly, the government,
almost any government,

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:50.970
but current example,
probably, is not

00:40:50.970 --> 00:40:54.060
good at doing these
sort of things.

00:40:54.060 --> 00:40:57.360
So we intend to tell the world.

00:40:57.360 --> 00:40:59.280
And we'll tell you what we know.

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:08.160
And it may be something
that completely comes back

00:41:08.160 --> 00:41:10.560
with a lot of
baggage of caveats.

00:41:10.560 --> 00:41:12.390
We think this, but
we can't prove it.

00:41:12.390 --> 00:41:15.510
It's possibly this,
but it might be that.

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:17.130
But we will share
the information

00:41:17.130 --> 00:41:18.650
for whatever we discover.

00:41:18.650 --> 00:41:24.180
And as we begin to go beyond
these kinds of signals

00:41:24.180 --> 00:41:27.150
that we've been looking
for and consider

00:41:27.150 --> 00:41:30.360
other technological
modifications such as--

00:41:30.360 --> 00:41:32.870
we heard about the
TRAPPIST-1 system.

00:41:32.870 --> 00:41:36.960
That's seven planets
orbiting a small dwarf

00:41:36.960 --> 00:41:43.650
star, all within the distance
of the orbit of Mercury.

00:41:43.650 --> 00:41:46.590
Those planets are different
distances from the star.

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:50.130
But what if, when we
get these great tools,

00:41:50.130 --> 00:41:53.610
and we actually make an
image of those seven planets,

00:41:53.610 --> 00:41:57.080
we find out that they all
look exactly the same?

00:41:57.080 --> 00:41:58.310
Now, they shouldn't.

00:41:58.310 --> 00:42:01.640
Naturally, they should reflect
their distance from the star.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:04.880
But maybe somebody out there
needed more real estate

00:42:04.880 --> 00:42:08.210
and they started transforming
some of these planets

00:42:08.210 --> 00:42:11.760
because they had enough
energy to be able to do that.

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:15.740
That kind of far-out thinking
is what's going on with respect

00:42:15.740 --> 00:42:18.270
to technosignatures these days.

00:42:18.270 --> 00:42:20.630
And that one's going
to be really loaded.

00:42:20.630 --> 00:42:24.200
I mean, if we ever discover
something like that,

00:42:24.200 --> 00:42:26.090
we'll tell you, but
it's going to have

00:42:26.090 --> 00:42:29.441
an awful lot of caveats.

00:42:29.441 --> 00:42:29.940
Yeah.

00:42:29.940 --> 00:42:32.370
- Jill, thanks for a great talk.

00:42:32.370 --> 00:42:34.890
I was really struck
by your metaphor

00:42:34.890 --> 00:42:36.900
of searching for
just the one-- we've

00:42:36.900 --> 00:42:40.090
searched one glass of water
out of an entire ocean.

00:42:40.090 --> 00:42:43.560
And sometimes, in
my own work, I feel

00:42:43.560 --> 00:42:46.130
like the challenges
are insurmountable,

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:52.830
whether it is just coping with
the distances, the tiny sizes

00:42:52.830 --> 00:42:55.440
of the signals that
we're searching for,

00:42:55.440 --> 00:42:58.080
or whether it's my
proposal got rejected,

00:42:58.080 --> 00:43:00.570
or funding for science is
going down, or whatever.

00:43:00.570 --> 00:43:05.010
And I was curious, over the arc
of your career, what you draw

00:43:05.010 --> 00:43:08.518
on for inspiration on bad days.

00:43:08.518 --> 00:43:12.150
- Ah, yeah, those bad days.

00:43:12.150 --> 00:43:15.300
It's the fact that
we can do today

00:43:15.300 --> 00:43:18.090
what we couldn't
conceive of a year ago.

00:43:18.090 --> 00:43:22.300
And next year, we'll be
doing so much better.

00:43:22.300 --> 00:43:24.366
So you get out of
bed, or at least I

00:43:24.366 --> 00:43:25.740
get out of bed in
the morning not

00:43:25.740 --> 00:43:28.340
thinking, today's the day
I'm going to get a signal,

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:31.710
because that's bound
to have a bad result.

00:43:31.710 --> 00:43:34.920
But you get out of bed thinking,
I gonna make the search better.

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:36.060
We'll be able to do this.

00:43:36.060 --> 00:43:37.410
We'll be able to do that.

00:43:37.410 --> 00:43:39.240
And maybe, eventually,
we're going

00:43:39.240 --> 00:43:43.500
to be doing the right thing
to find whatever is out there.

00:43:43.500 --> 00:43:48.450
So it's simply to look at
14 or 15 orders of magnitude

00:43:48.450 --> 00:43:53.040
improvement over Frank
Drake's first search in 1960

00:43:53.040 --> 00:43:57.270
and understand that with
exponentials, the best

00:43:57.270 --> 00:43:59.500
stuff happens in
the last folding,

00:43:59.500 --> 00:44:02.400
right, the last factor of 2.

00:44:02.400 --> 00:44:06.240
So yes, it's the
opportunity to do something

00:44:06.240 --> 00:44:08.990
better than we did in the past.

00:44:08.990 --> 00:44:09.490
- Thank you.

00:44:09.490 --> 00:44:11.170
Your career is an
inspiration to us all.

00:44:11.170 --> 00:44:13.092
- Oh, Thank you, Laurie.

