00:44:57.850 --> 00:45:02.950
is 10 billion times fainter
than the star, the Sun,

00:45:02.950 --> 00:45:05.030
if you were looking
at it from a distance.

00:45:05.030 --> 00:45:09.100
So what you have to try and do
is block out that bright star.

00:45:09.100 --> 00:45:12.240
You can do it with an instrument
inside the telescope called

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:15.430
a coronagraph, which
actually takes that starlight

00:45:15.430 --> 00:45:17.710
and scatters it far away.

00:45:17.710 --> 00:45:20.800
But it's hard to get a factor
of 10 billion that way.

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:22.960
But the star shade is just that.

00:45:22.960 --> 00:45:25.540
It flies in front
of the telescope,

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:27.610
and it serves the same purpose--

00:45:27.610 --> 00:45:32.690
blocking out the star light so
that you have an opportunity,

00:45:32.690 --> 00:45:37.750
perhaps, to be able to
image the faint planets very

00:45:37.750 --> 00:45:40.185
close to, around
that bright star.

00:45:40.185 --> 00:45:43.990
- Is there a distance
to where it's

00:45:43.990 --> 00:45:46.450
no longer efficient to use it?

00:45:46.450 --> 00:45:50.110
- We actually have
not flown one yet.

00:45:50.110 --> 00:45:55.570
We hope that WFIRST will fly one
as a technology demonstrator.

00:45:55.570 --> 00:45:58.174
And it is flying--

00:45:58.174 --> 00:45:59.590
oh, I can't remember
the distance.

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:00.520
Can anybody remember?

00:46:00.520 --> 00:46:04.780
I think it's a few hundred
kilometers out in front

00:46:04.780 --> 00:46:09.290
of the telescope to
cast this big shadow.

00:46:09.290 --> 00:46:13.210
- Do you give any credence to
the TV show Ancient Aliens or--

00:46:13.210 --> 00:46:14.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:15.700 --> 00:46:19.010
- I think science fiction
is a marvelous way

00:46:19.010 --> 00:46:23.060
to help us think about things
that we can't conceive of.

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:25.085
That wouldn't be
one of my choices.

00:46:25.085 --> 00:46:27.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:27.770 --> 00:46:31.100
But I think science fiction
is actually fantastic.

00:46:31.100 --> 00:46:37.490
It gives us examples of
stories, where life was detected

00:46:37.490 --> 00:46:39.770
and we didn't realize
that it was alive.

00:46:39.770 --> 00:46:41.420
It was a life that
we didn't yet know,

00:46:41.420 --> 00:46:43.640
and we didn't realize
that it was alive.

00:46:43.640 --> 00:46:47.480
And we can explore
those kinds of ideas

00:46:47.480 --> 00:46:50.900
and think about how
we use them to keep

00:46:50.900 --> 00:46:55.910
our minds open to
future discoveries

00:46:55.910 --> 00:46:58.592
of the undiscovered.

00:46:58.592 --> 00:47:00.550
- You've been doing this
for a number of years.

00:47:00.550 --> 00:47:01.936
And I'm just curious about--

00:47:01.936 --> 00:47:03.310
there were a couple
of times when

00:47:03.310 --> 00:47:06.130
you thought you got
a signal, and what

00:47:06.130 --> 00:47:07.240
that experience was like.

00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:11.080
And if it turned out it
wasn't, what kind of things

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:14.500
would cause you to
get that-- yeah.

00:47:14.500 --> 00:47:18.400
- That adrenaline
rush is unbelievable.

00:47:18.400 --> 00:47:22.840
And you get so excited,
you do stupid things.

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:26.650
And so every time we have one
of these, our list of checklists

00:47:26.650 --> 00:47:29.230
and what you do next
gets longer because we

00:47:29.230 --> 00:47:31.090
learn from our mistakes.

00:47:31.090 --> 00:47:35.620
Yes, the one-- the one
that was most spectacular

00:47:35.620 --> 00:47:41.650
for me personally
was, we observed

00:47:41.650 --> 00:47:44.860
with two widely separated
telescopes in this project

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:47.260
that we call Phoenix.

00:47:47.260 --> 00:47:49.900
We were using the National
Radio Astronomy Observatory

00:47:49.900 --> 00:47:50.530
telescope.

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:54.460
And we had a second
telescope in Georgia.

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:56.710
And the telescope in
Georgia got hit by lightning

00:47:56.710 --> 00:47:59.410
and it fried a disk drive.

00:47:59.410 --> 00:48:01.940
So it took FedEx a few days to
get in there with a new disk

00:48:01.940 --> 00:48:02.440
drive.

00:48:02.440 --> 00:48:05.000
But we still have this
telescope in West Virginia.

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:05.500
Right?

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:06.730
So what can we do?

00:48:06.730 --> 00:48:08.920
We don't have the
differential Doppler signature

00:48:08.920 --> 00:48:12.610
from the two telescopes to help
us distinguish interference

00:48:12.610 --> 00:48:14.410
from the real thing.

00:48:14.410 --> 00:48:17.560
So you look at the star
that we were pointing at.

00:48:17.560 --> 00:48:18.660
You see a signal.

00:48:18.660 --> 00:48:21.670
It's a picket fence in
the frequency time plane.

00:48:21.670 --> 00:48:23.710
That's not natural.

00:48:23.710 --> 00:48:24.520
And you look away.

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:25.597
The signal goes away.

00:48:25.597 --> 00:48:26.680
You come back on the star.

00:48:26.680 --> 00:48:27.910
The signal's there.

00:48:27.910 --> 00:48:30.560
Look off in a different
direction, signal goes away.

00:48:30.560 --> 00:48:31.990
Come back on the star--

00:48:31.990 --> 00:48:33.334
hours of this.

00:48:33.334 --> 00:48:35.500
And early in the process,
I thought, well, you know,

00:48:35.500 --> 00:48:39.580
that picket fence has a very
regular spacing in frequency.

00:48:39.580 --> 00:48:42.760
Why don't I query
our database and see

00:48:42.760 --> 00:48:45.910
if we've ever seen that
frequency spacing before

00:48:45.910 --> 00:48:48.045
from another part of the sky.

00:48:48.045 --> 00:48:48.670
And I did that.

00:48:48.670 --> 00:48:49.340
I wrote the program.

00:48:49.340 --> 00:48:49.970
It compiled.

00:48:49.970 --> 00:48:53.420
But I was in a hurry, and I
didn't do very good formatting.

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:55.780
It was kind of a mess
when I read it out.

00:48:55.780 --> 00:48:58.210
And indeed, it was the
right question to ask.

00:48:58.210 --> 00:49:01.390
And indeed, we had seen it
from other parts on the sky.

00:49:01.390 --> 00:49:04.000
But the columns
were mixed up, and I

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:07.150
didn't see that we
actually knew that it

00:49:07.150 --> 00:49:09.580
wasn't coming from that star.

00:49:09.580 --> 00:49:11.350
So we spent the day.

00:49:11.350 --> 00:49:12.220
The star set.

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:15.850
And the nature of the signal
was changing over time,

00:49:15.850 --> 00:49:19.150
changing in a way
that we knew that it

00:49:19.150 --> 00:49:22.600
was rising above
us to the zenith

00:49:22.600 --> 00:49:25.450
rather than setting in the west.

00:49:25.450 --> 00:49:28.030
So we went off, and
had some dinner,

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:32.080
and did some internet
research, and figured out

00:49:32.080 --> 00:49:35.410
it was the SOHO spacecraft
orbiting the sun,

00:49:35.410 --> 00:49:39.520
getting in a tiny little
side lobe of the telescope.

00:49:39.520 --> 00:49:42.460
And that was really
disappointing.

00:49:42.460 --> 00:49:44.530
But you know what?

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:46.360
Our colleagues
back in California

00:49:46.360 --> 00:49:50.050
were all excited because
we'd shared this with them.

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:54.220
So they stayed up through the
night waiting for the star

00:49:54.220 --> 00:49:57.386
to rise again because I forgot
to call them and tell them it

00:49:57.386 --> 00:49:57.886
wasn't.

00:49:57.886 --> 00:49:58.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:58.980 --> 00:50:01.400
And I have paid--

00:50:01.400 --> 00:50:04.780
I have bought so many drinks
in bars over the years

00:50:04.780 --> 00:50:07.485
to apologize for
that bad behavior.

00:50:07.485 --> 00:50:08.860
- Thank you for
that great story.

00:50:08.860 --> 00:50:11.551
- OK.

00:50:11.551 --> 00:50:12.050
- Hi.

00:50:12.050 --> 00:50:14.120
Can you describe
what our planet looks

00:50:14.120 --> 00:50:16.790
like to the observers that
are on another planet,

00:50:16.790 --> 00:50:17.660
looking for us?

00:50:17.660 --> 00:50:19.520
- It does.

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:25.550
The strongest radio
signals that we actually

00:50:25.550 --> 00:50:34.130
have are associated with the
radars that are looking--

00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:36.200
over the horizon radars.

00:50:36.200 --> 00:50:38.060
And the most
numerous transmitters

00:50:38.060 --> 00:50:41.780
we have are still the
ground-based broadcast

00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:44.180
television and radio stations.

00:50:44.180 --> 00:50:46.760
And so if you looked
at our planet,

00:50:46.760 --> 00:50:49.370
and you were looking at
the right frequencies,

00:50:49.370 --> 00:50:53.570
you would see it sparkle
as those transmitters came

00:50:53.570 --> 00:50:56.140
over the limb as
the planet rotates.

00:50:56.140 --> 00:50:59.900
And you would see various
frequencies light up

00:50:59.900 --> 00:51:01.490
from these signals.

00:51:01.490 --> 00:51:03.200
And indeed, there's
a great study

00:51:03.200 --> 00:51:06.890
by Woody Sullivan a long time
ago that we need to redo.

00:51:06.890 --> 00:51:09.860
But you could actually--
back in the day, when

00:51:09.860 --> 00:51:12.830
it was all broadcast
television, you

00:51:12.830 --> 00:51:15.290
could figure out
the different parts

00:51:15.290 --> 00:51:20.360
of the globe assigned different
television stations, slightly

00:51:20.360 --> 00:51:22.220
different frequencies.

00:51:22.220 --> 00:51:27.050
So you might be able to conclude
that geopolitical structure

00:51:27.050 --> 00:51:30.800
on the planet was not
global, had some differences.

00:51:30.800 --> 00:51:34.020
But-- how we doing?

00:51:34.020 --> 00:51:36.585
[APPLAUSE]

00:51:37.543 --> 00:51:38.980
- Thank you very much.

00:51:38.980 --> 00:51:40.417
- You're very welcome.

00:51:43.936 --> 00:51:45.810
- Well, that was certainly
worth waiting for.

00:51:45.810 --> 00:51:47.470
Thank you, again, Jill.

00:51:47.470 --> 00:51:47.970
Thank you.

00:51:47.970 --> 00:51:51.330
And it falls to me to try
to say a few things that

00:51:51.330 --> 00:51:54.160
connect what we heard today.

00:51:54.160 --> 00:51:56.860
And before I do that, I
just would like to point out

00:51:56.860 --> 00:51:58.860
something that's kind of
a preamble to what I'll

00:51:58.860 --> 00:52:01.140
say in a minute, which
is, this is the list

00:52:01.140 --> 00:52:04.860
of countries where people are
now listening and watching

00:52:04.860 --> 00:52:06.630
what's happening here--

00:52:06.630 --> 00:52:10.620
the United States, Canada,
Belgium, Argentina, India,

00:52:10.620 --> 00:52:14.100
the Netherlands, Turkey, Chile,
the United Kingdom, Israel,

00:52:14.100 --> 00:52:17.070
Sweden, and Taiwan,
as far as we know.

00:52:17.070 --> 00:52:18.750
So there are
hundreds or thousands

00:52:18.750 --> 00:52:21.780
of people watching this live.

00:52:21.780 --> 00:52:24.780
And that's been
possible for the last--

00:52:24.780 --> 00:52:26.340
I don't know--
decade or something.

00:52:26.340 --> 00:52:28.710
It's become much
more popular now.

00:52:28.710 --> 00:52:32.130
And you know, even
in places as far away

00:52:32.130 --> 00:52:36.130
as Taiwan, people are clearly
up in the night watching this.

00:52:36.130 --> 00:52:38.850
So thank you very much, Taiwan.

00:52:38.850 --> 00:52:45.180
And what this is allowing here
is an example of Radcliffe.

00:52:45.180 --> 00:52:48.600
My friend Immaculata here, my
colleague, Immaculata de Vivo,

00:52:48.600 --> 00:52:51.120
the other director for
science, said, you know,

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:54.030
Radcliffe is being
discovered and used

00:52:54.030 --> 00:52:56.070
to be part of the undiscovered.

00:52:56.070 --> 00:53:01.500
And technology is allowing
us to talk to more people.

00:53:01.500 --> 00:53:04.180
And what we're doing is we're
transmitting information.

00:53:04.180 --> 00:53:05.760
And I think the
theme that you heard

00:53:05.760 --> 00:53:08.640
today is that we've gotten
to the point where there

00:53:08.640 --> 00:53:11.220
is so much information
and our ability

00:53:11.220 --> 00:53:13.830
to gather this information,
and to put it together,

00:53:13.830 --> 00:53:17.670
and to process it using
ever faster computers

00:53:17.670 --> 00:53:22.470
is necessarily changing how
we emit the truth about how

00:53:22.470 --> 00:53:23.742
we do science.

00:53:23.742 --> 00:53:25.200
So in other words,
you used to have

00:53:25.200 --> 00:53:29.400
to share data with
close colleagues

00:53:29.400 --> 00:53:31.740
and not share beyond
there, because there

00:53:31.740 --> 00:53:33.690
wasn't so much to go around.

00:53:33.690 --> 00:53:35.550
But now, in almost
every field, there's

00:53:35.550 --> 00:53:39.000
too much information for
people to process on their own.

00:53:39.000 --> 00:53:40.920
So you heard about teams.

00:53:40.920 --> 00:53:44.160
You heard about people
using new algorithms

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:47.670
and finding cures for
diseases or finding out

00:53:47.670 --> 00:53:50.190
that Alzheimer's
might have something

00:53:50.190 --> 00:53:52.650
to do with viruses,
when that was clearly

00:53:52.650 --> 00:53:55.360
not something anybody
was looking for.

00:53:55.360 --> 00:53:58.630
And so stepping
back and saying--

00:53:58.630 --> 00:54:01.900
I think Nate's word that he used
several times was "reframing."

00:54:01.900 --> 00:54:04.570
We have to reframe
the kinds of questions

00:54:04.570 --> 00:54:07.660
we can ask in the presence
of so much information.

00:54:07.660 --> 00:54:10.230
And you heard a lot of people
use the phrase "big data."

00:54:10.230 --> 00:54:11.980
I don't particularly
like that phrase

00:54:11.980 --> 00:54:15.520
because what's important-- and
I do do data science sometimes

00:54:15.520 --> 00:54:16.546
in my day job.

00:54:16.546 --> 00:54:17.920
And I know what's
important there

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:20.740
is what you heard some of here
today, which is combining.

00:54:20.740 --> 00:54:22.450
You just heard Jill
tell you about so

00:54:22.450 --> 00:54:25.060
many different telescopes
being used in the search

00:54:25.060 --> 00:54:26.740
to answer one question.

00:54:26.740 --> 00:54:28.750
So you have a lot
of cases where you

00:54:28.750 --> 00:54:31.030
have a lot of different
kinds of information being

00:54:31.030 --> 00:54:32.850
brought to bear on a question.

00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:34.870
And we like to call
that "wide data."

00:54:34.870 --> 00:54:36.660
You can think of it
as data diversity.

00:54:36.660 --> 00:54:37.240
OK?

00:54:37.240 --> 00:54:41.470
So there's this plethora
of information that's

00:54:41.470 --> 00:54:43.330
just getting larger and larger.

00:54:43.330 --> 00:54:45.640
And we're inviting more
people into the conversation.

00:54:45.640 --> 00:54:47.560
You heard about Citizen Science.

00:54:47.560 --> 00:54:50.680
Sometimes you hear this phrase,
"democratization of data."

00:54:50.680 --> 00:54:53.530
Most importantly, you heard
the unbelievable questions

00:54:53.530 --> 00:54:55.940
from the Barnstable
High School students.

00:54:55.940 --> 00:54:58.060
Thank you again.

00:54:58.060 --> 00:54:59.800
And you heard about transitions.

00:54:59.800 --> 00:55:02.860
When we were talking, for
example, about climate,

00:55:02.860 --> 00:55:05.320
you heard that there
are some transitions,

00:55:05.320 --> 00:55:07.570
in some cases, that we just
want, like the transition

00:55:07.570 --> 00:55:10.360
that we were talking about today
about how we teach education,

00:55:10.360 --> 00:55:15.230
and some that we need, like the
way that we handle the climate.

00:55:15.230 --> 00:55:17.050
And so we're at
this point where we

00:55:17.050 --> 00:55:22.600
have to have a conversation with
the public about science, which

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:24.680
I was trying to think about it.

00:55:24.680 --> 00:55:29.020
And it's a little bit
about how you're a parent.

00:55:29.020 --> 00:55:32.080
And so I'm lucky enough that
my parents are here today.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:33.790
My daughter happens
to be in Morocco.

00:55:33.790 --> 00:55:37.330
She's not on the list
of people watching this.

00:55:37.330 --> 00:55:37.830
But--

00:55:37.830 --> 00:55:40.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:40.180 --> 00:55:43.510
But thinking about being a
parent and being a child,

00:55:43.510 --> 00:55:46.780
there's this need to respect
your parents that you're

00:55:46.780 --> 00:55:48.160
taught when you're very young.

00:55:48.160 --> 00:55:50.410
And there's a need to
respect scientists.

00:55:50.410 --> 00:55:52.630
And there's a need to
respect what's in the book

00:55:52.630 --> 00:55:55.840
and what you have to learn
from what's in the book and all

00:55:55.840 --> 00:55:58.600
that stuff that Stuart told
us this morning about what

00:55:58.600 --> 00:56:00.220
you have to know.

00:56:00.220 --> 00:56:03.890
But then at some point, many
points in your life as a child,

00:56:03.890 --> 00:56:05.920
you have to learn
when to ask questions,

00:56:05.920 --> 00:56:07.990
and when to stop
just completely--

00:56:07.990 --> 00:56:09.490
I'm sorry to my parents--

00:56:09.490 --> 00:56:15.040
respecting authority, and
just go a little bit outside.

00:56:15.040 --> 00:56:18.220
I think earlier I called it
something like out-of-the-book

00:56:18.220 --> 00:56:18.820
thinking.

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:19.460
OK?

00:56:19.460 --> 00:56:21.940
So going beyond what
your parents tell you.

00:56:21.940 --> 00:56:24.610
But the thing is,
the danger here

00:56:24.610 --> 00:56:26.800
is that we need to
admit uncertainty.

00:56:26.800 --> 00:56:28.060
We need to admit ignorance.

00:56:28.060 --> 00:56:31.330
We need to admit the mist
that Stuart was talking about,

00:56:31.330 --> 00:56:33.790
this fog that we look
at science through.

00:56:33.790 --> 00:56:35.560
And if people haven't
had the experience

00:56:35.560 --> 00:56:37.300
and they haven't been
taught in the right way,

00:56:37.300 --> 00:56:38.980
they are going to
come to the conclusion

00:56:38.980 --> 00:56:41.600
that that means we don't
know what we're doing.

00:56:41.600 --> 00:56:43.420
And if you have
good parents, you

00:56:43.420 --> 00:56:45.620
don't ever come to that
conclusion about them.

00:56:45.620 --> 00:56:46.120
Right?

00:56:46.120 --> 00:56:47.410
You still respect them.

00:56:47.410 --> 00:56:49.240
But you can question them.

00:56:49.240 --> 00:56:52.030
And that's how scientists have
to behave with their colleagues

00:56:52.030 --> 00:56:52.990
as well.

00:56:52.990 --> 00:56:54.880
And you heard these
stories about people

00:56:54.880 --> 00:56:56.410
having data in a
drawer that they

00:56:56.410 --> 00:56:59.560
didn't want to put out there
because it was going to violate

00:56:59.560 --> 00:57:02.740
conventional wisdom, and it
was going to question authority

00:57:02.740 --> 00:57:05.090
in a way that they
thought they might not get

00:57:05.090 --> 00:57:07.150
tenure or something like that.

00:57:07.150 --> 00:57:09.550
And I think that when we
have much information,

00:57:09.550 --> 00:57:10.330
and a lot of it--

00:57:10.330 --> 00:57:13.360
you heard people talking about
open data and open software.

00:57:13.360 --> 00:57:17.260
We have this need and this
desire now for transparency.

00:57:17.260 --> 00:57:20.020
And yeah, we'll get to the point
of more reproducible research.

00:57:20.020 --> 00:57:22.390
But really, it's not about
reproducing research.

00:57:22.390 --> 00:57:25.660
It's about opening
new avenues and about

00:57:25.660 --> 00:57:29.650
this idea of the undiscovered.

00:57:29.650 --> 00:57:34.420
And I think that there are
so many questions to be asked

00:57:34.420 --> 00:57:39.500
in this vast realm of
ignorance-- thank you, Stuart--

00:57:39.500 --> 00:57:43.220
that I would just
like to close--

00:57:43.220 --> 00:57:44.680
I want to thank a few people.

00:57:44.680 --> 00:57:46.630
And then, what I would
like is to capture

00:57:46.630 --> 00:57:48.640
that spirit of the
undiscovered one more

00:57:48.640 --> 00:57:54.460
time by asking Caylee to have
her poem read for her by us

00:57:54.460 --> 00:57:55.790
one more time.

00:57:55.790 --> 00:57:59.320
But I guess my
closing thought is

00:57:59.320 --> 00:58:01.960
that in this era of
so much information

00:58:01.960 --> 00:58:04.870
that you heard about
across all of these fields

00:58:04.870 --> 00:58:11.050
and this so much more
inviting, instead of capable--

00:58:11.050 --> 00:58:13.930
or capabilities that
we have in terms

00:58:13.930 --> 00:58:16.300
of ways of dealing with
it, and the more people who

00:58:16.300 --> 00:58:19.510
are involved, we
can't hide any more.

00:58:19.510 --> 00:58:23.080
We have to be open
about our ignorance.

00:58:23.080 --> 00:58:26.530
And we have to somehow do
it in a way where we still

00:58:26.530 --> 00:58:31.690
respect our parents or
the people who gave us

00:58:31.690 --> 00:58:34.050
this education that we
had that led us to ask

00:58:34.050 --> 00:58:36.419
these intelligent questions.

00:58:36.419 --> 00:58:37.960
And so with that,
I would really like

00:58:37.960 --> 00:58:41.710
to thank all of the
speakers for bringing us

00:58:41.710 --> 00:58:43.040
this wonderful set of talks.

00:58:43.040 --> 00:58:45.426
So let's have round of
applause for the speakers.

00:58:45.426 --> 00:58:46.412
Thank you.

00:58:46.412 --> 00:58:49.370
[APPLAUSE]

00:58:52.330 --> 00:58:55.210
And then you see so many
people scurrying around,

00:58:55.210 --> 00:58:57.120
making this all look effortless.

00:58:57.120 --> 00:58:59.980
But there really was about
a year of preparation

00:58:59.980 --> 00:59:01.896
for this event.

00:59:01.896 --> 00:59:03.520
And I can't name them
all one at a time

00:59:03.520 --> 00:59:05.436
because there are just
so many people helping.

00:59:05.436 --> 00:59:07.330
But I would just like
to thank the staff who

00:59:07.330 --> 00:59:10.008
participated in making this
such a fantastic event.

00:59:10.008 --> 00:59:12.864
[APPLAUSE]

00:59:14.292 --> 00:59:16.210
Thank you.

00:59:16.210 --> 00:59:20.750
And I'll remind you that,
after Caylee reads her poem,

00:59:20.750 --> 00:59:22.820
we can move to the
place where there

00:59:22.820 --> 00:59:25.480
are copies of her poem,
the poster session.

00:59:25.480 --> 00:59:27.650
We'll continue next
